segments.text: First, Mr. Ashton, tell us a little bit about your early life, including the names of your parents, the places and dates of their birth and death if you know them, the place and date of your birth, and schools you attended up to going to college.
Well, I was born in Trouters, Rhode Island, October 17, 1908, on Laurel Hill Avenue, which, to be honest about it, was a rather slum area.
I don't remember my father and mother very well because they died when I was quite young, both of them within three months of each other with pneumonia.
My father, incidentally, was an ice man.
Now, that's an occupation that no longer exists.
And I was stuck in an orphanage.
And when I say an orphanage, I don't mean one likened to these that you have here in this beautiful state of Texas.
This was a prison.
It was one of these places run by charity.
You were awful lucky if you had shoes that matched.
We had secondhand toothbrushes and so forth.
Well, I was taken out of there at the age of nine by two elderly people up in Massachusetts who didn't know what a hellion they were getting.
They were very wonderful people.
And I went to school in Massachusetts and finished high school in Medway High School.
And I had already made up my mind.
I was quite an athlete when I was a kid.
I'd already made up my mind four or five years
before I finished that I was going to Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island.
My football coach, incidentally, was a Brown man.
And with my high scholastic standing and his pull, I got into Brown.
I stayed there a couple of years.
And let me tell you, that place is prohibitive.
Even in those days, I entered Brown in 1926.
And it was one of the costliest schools in America then.
I met a fellow there from Baylor.
And he gave me a big line about Texas.
I was about to run out of money.
I had no folks, of course.
And he kept chipping at me and chipping at me.
And finally, I just hopped a train and I came down to Baylor.
The man you met from Baylor, was he a Baylor graduate who was teaching at Brown?
Yes, he was a Baylor graduate.
And he was up there working on an advanced degree and teaching history at Brown University.
Incidentally, the way we met, I worked for a detective agency working nights in Providence, Rhode Island.
And I was out on the street all hours of the night, of course.
And he did a lot of walking.
He was very lonesome.
And we had to wear these little brown hats with a white button.
And so I bumped into him several times late at night.
We struck up a little conversation.
We became quite friendly and that's how I landed here in Texas in 1928.
And he had a job for me at Baylor.
I flourished at Baylor.
I got a degree at Baylor.
And then I went, I got a job, my first school job was coaching football.
What was your major at Baylor?
I double majored in English and History.
Did you participate in any kind of sports while you were there?
I was ineligible.
I was quite a track man in the East, but I was ineligible as bailiff.
I never could become eligible.
You can today, now, after years of residence.
I see.
You were ineligible.
But I worked with a track team there.
I helped train the track team with Ralph Wilson.
You were ineligible.
Was that because you were an out-of-state resident?
No, because I'd run at Brown.
I see.
I participated in another school, and therefore you were ineligible.
That's right.
for the rest of your college.
That's right.
You had been, what, two years at Brown?
Yes.
And then you did two years at Baylor.
Yes.
OK. Then you say you began as a high school coach after that.
Where did you?
Not only that, I was not only the high school coach, but I was the principal of the grammar school.
Where was this?
This was in Lorena, Texas.
It's about 15 miles out of Waco on the way to Austin.
For how long did you... Two years.
Two years.
And then where did you go?
Then I went to Gorman, Texas as a football coach and principal of the elementary school.
And that, thank the good Lord, is where I met my wife.
Uh-huh.
Now, that one year.
And I wrote a little letter up to Massachusetts just for the fun of it.
to my old superintendent and football coach, and he wrote back a little note with a contract in it that said, sign it, we need you up here to teach English.
I signed it, I went up there, stayed a year, came back, married my wife, we went back, stayed another 10 years.
And on the way down on that last year, I said to my wife, if I get a job in Texas, would you like to move back?
Well, I'm not gonna tell you what she said, but she said yes.
And I did.
How did you happen to get the job at A&M?
Well, that's a strange thing.
I just happened to visit at Baylor.
And the old fellow out there that I love very much, a fellow named Sparkman, Dr. Sparkman, wonderful old fellow.
I dropped in there to pay him a little visit.
He said, I knew he was in the state.
He said, and I just sent a note down to A&M to Tommy Mayo and told him that you would be down there
to be interviewed for a job.
He said, they need some English teachers.
And I told him, well, Sparky, I'll go.
So I came down.
And in five minutes, Tommy said, you're hired.
And Tommy May was a wonderful fellow.
So I have come to understand from a number of people who I've talked with who were students of his or talked with him or something.
Wonderful fellow.
And you joined the faculty then in 1946?
That's right.
As what, an instructor in English?
Instructor in English, and I was out at the airfield.
So you were in the basic division teaching?
No, it wasn't called a basic then.
That was the year when we had that big influx of veterans, and they were out at the old airfield out here west of
On the way to power.
Right.
Okay.
That was in 46.
That was before the basic division was created.
That's right.
Who was out at the annex then?
Well, there were six of us English teachers out there, and I don't remember.
Some basic courses were taught out there.
That's what you mean.
Yes, yes.
But the basic division is something entirely different than that.
Now, we were teaching English 103 and 104 out there, six of us out there.
And then they had, I think, math was out there.
And I don't remember what else was out there, but I remember Tom Harrington was the coordinator or dean or whatever.
We had a raft of fellows out there.
But it was all freshmen out there?
Yeah.
Yes.
Where did you live then?
Well, I lived out there in one of those...
barracks or whatever you call it, you know, the ones that fronted the highway.
They weren't down where the students lived.
I guess you'd call them officers' quarters, I presume.
You had an apartment in one of the buildings then.
Yes.
Did all the faculty live in one or two of the buildings?
Well, there were several of those long things, you know.
Yes, we all lived out there.
No, some of them lived way down, further down beyond where the students lived.
We all lived out there at the annex.
How long did you stay out at the annex then?
I think it was a couple of years or a year and a half, and then Tommy called me into the main campus.
You know, I'm not very good at dates.
I can't remember really what happened last week, so I'm a little hazy on dates.
Well, to a certain extent, specific dates are not that important.
They're not important.
When you came back, when you came to the main campus and after a couple years out of Gen X, did you continue to teach primarily freshman courses or did you have more upperclassmen at that point?
No, it wasn't very long before Dr. Mayo gave me some upper class work to do, sophomore level work.
And he called me in one day and asked me to teach 319, which is a report writing course and so forth and so on.
So for quite a few years there I taught several levels.
How did you become director or head of the Aggie Players?
That's a strange question and it's a stranger answer.
I don't know.
I just... Tommy Mayo asked me if I'd take over the Aggie Players and I said yes.
And that was it.
Now you will explain that.
Had you had any prior training, experience, or whatever in theater arts?
Oh, yes.
Up in Massachusetts when I was teaching there, I worked with a stock company for about 10 years.
And I did a great deal of acting.
I never had any courses in college or at the university level in any theater.
I learned quite a bit working with this group because we had some very special people working.
This was in Medway, Massachusetts.
I worked with the Medway players.
And I also became president of that for a couple of years.
It was a stock company.
We made some money, and we gave it away.
You know, it was a non-profit thing.
So you had had a good bit of practical experience.
Oh, yes, I had a great deal of practical experience.
What had been the past history of this organization?
Well, it was very hazy.
The Aggie Players itself
has a name, came into existence in 1946.

And prior to that, as I say, back to 1876, student organizations and faculty organizations on this campus had, under many different names, endeavored to put on shows, plays of all kinds and of all descriptions, none of which lasted very long.
They were very short-lived.
That is the organization.
Yes.
Can you tell us something about the creation of the Aggie Players in 1946?
No.
I wasn't interested in the Aggie Players in 1946.
I was interested, but I don't know what went on because I didn't have anything to do with them.
I didn't take them over until 1950.
So you were off campus at the time they were created?
No, I was on campus.
Well, I mean, but you were out at the annex.
No.
Yes, yes, yes, a couple of years.
Yes, yes.
So then your first contact was in 50 when Dr. Mayo asked you to take it over.
That's right.
and uh what uh it was under student activities at that time so it was it was not under the english department it was uh not the aggie players no um
There were two courses called English 381 and 382 that had been created by whom I don't know.
And one of them was called play production and the other one was called stagecraft.
And just to be honest, they were not very good courses.
They were not very good.
Those had been in existence probably a couple of years when I took it over.
And I was assigned those two courses.
That was at the time you became director of the Aggie Players?
Right, yeah.
What was the makeup of the Aggie Players as an organization when you took them over?
Well, as I told you, they all quit when I took it over.
But, I mean, it had been just a kind of a student social organization that did put on play?
Well, you used the word social.
I didn't, but I'll abide by that.
Well, in other words, it was a student organization.
Right.
whose purpose was to put on plays for entertainment.
Right.
It was not, say, a function of the English department.
No.
However, an English instructor was the director of the plays.
Then you said you took it over and everybody who was a member quit.
What did you do then?
Well, I just issued a call in the battalion for a cast call to do the first show.
And a few people showed up.
Do you remember what your first show was?
Yes, there they are, right there on the old wall.
That's every show that I've ever done here, right there.
The first show I did was Kind Lady.
I forgot who wrote it now.
Now...
This may sound like kind of a silly question, but at the point you took over the Aggie Players, of course, it was almost entirely an all-male military school.
And obviously, with a play like Kind Lady, you would have a female person.
Where did you get your females to?
There was never any problem in getting ladies
to work with the Aggie players.
We used secretaries, we used some faculty wives, we had people from town if they wanted to come out.
Any lady in the community was eligible to join the Aggie players.
We never had any problem in getting ladies.
Even though it was a student organization, non-students quite regularly belonged to it.
Over the years, I've had several wives of deans, and when Dr. Morgan was president, his wife was a member of the Aggie Place and worked in several plays.
In fact, she's quite a brilliant woman.
And she wrote quite a few plays, and I did one of her plays.
And she acted in it for me, with me.
She's a brilliant woman.
What would you say would be some of your outstanding plays that you have done over the years?
Most interesting, most difficult?
Well, probably the two.
would be Shakespeare's Macbeth, which, you know, one does not stir the bones of Shakespeare.
But I studied that with another gentleman who is now not on the faculty, but a very brilliant man.
And we did a great deal of study of witchcraft and of that particular period.
And we changed it a little.
Now, don't misunderstand me.
I did not touch one single line
of Shakespeare, but we did rearrange some scenes and we portrayed witches other than had been previously portrayed.
And I prefer not to go into that now because I don't think you've got that kind of time.
And the other show that I have a great liking for was Death of a Salesman, which I think is one of America's great plays of this century.
That's just my personal opinion.
But those two shows, oh, there are many shows that stick out in my mind that I've done.
I've done Oedipus Rex.
I like that, too, by Sarkozy.
I did both versions.
The one, you know, with the Greek costume.
I did the modern version by Hanoi.
Oh, I don't know.
I'd hate to list the shows.
Because I'm in this business, or I got into this business because I love two things.
I love theater and I like my kids.
I mean, my students.
They're wonderful kids here at A&M.
Now, don't you ever forget it.
And that's why I stayed in the business.
We've had our ups and downs and mostly downs.
But it's been fun.
And to me, it's been rewarding.
So I wouldn't want to.
pick out too many shows, but those in particular, I think that death of a salesman will eventually rate right up there with the top stuff that's been produced in America.
That's a wonderful, wonderful show.

You mentioned earlier that at the time you took over the Aggie Players, there were two courses in the English department having to do with theater arts, and you were named as the instructor at those at that time.
To what extent has the theater arts section grown in the English department?
Well, that's quite a story.
The Texas Educational Theater Association was formed in 1950, and I was a charter member of that, and eventually I became president of it, two terms.
I've been also secretary of it and held several other offices in it.
It's an organization that

includes all the uh not all but any of the university and college people in texas who are interested in promoting good theater in texas and we have a convention once a year i'm not going to go into that but that organization is primarily responsible for cataloging and making up different
curricula that are now used throughout the colleges in Texas.
And I had quite a hand in that.
And that's where our six basic courses started in that organization.
We had help from all of the members to make up these courses.
And that's where they show.
And of course, acting, scene design, directing, and playwriting, and so forth and so on.
And we suggested that the colleges adopt those.
And we've got all our syllabi on those things.
And that's how it started.
And right now, we've got 19 courses here that are offered at the university, accredited.
And I'll have to say that
I'm responsible for the general outline of all of these courses.
And when I hired this young fellow, Wink, a few years ago, I turned over several courses to him on a technical level, and he's added and deleted quite a bit in there.
So we have quite a bit of theater work that's offered today in the catalog.
And I changed the thing from English to theater arts.
But after all, most universities, they call it drama.
Now, to me, the word drama means the play.
That's all it means.
And if I'm going to take a script and put it on in a building or out in a pasture somewhere, that is theater.
That's theater.
And so that's why.
And then, of course, we added the word art to it.
on general principles.
So that's why I have, I name these courses theater arts.
I don't think there's but one or two schools in the state that have any titles like that.
Most of them are drama.
Drama.
And a good many of them are speech, and that's... Well, many of them have it as a separate speech and drama department, do they not?
Yes.
As opposed to being in the English department.
Oh, yes, yes, yes, sure.
Is A&M the only one that has it in the English department?
Well, I'm not going to say they're the only one, but I think so.
I'm going to say something.
I don't know whether you want to delete this or not.
Well, we'll leave that up to you.
I'm going to say this, that for two years I have had on somebody's desk up there a complete program whereby A&M can offer a B.A.
degree in theater.
And it has been
looked at and looked at favorably by TEA, and it hasn't happened yet.
I'm not going to say any more now because, not that it makes any difference to you or me either, but we have all of the facilities here to offer a degree.
So you didn't get that, I don't know.
When you first took over the Aggie Players in 1950, what facility did you use for putting on your place?
I just got through telling you, we had a leaky assembly hall.
And I had six great big leak holes.
You don't know what one of those is, but they were about this long, about this big round.
And they were not very good.
That's all we had.
You called them what?
The six things you had were called what?
Lekos.
L-E-K-O-S. That's a light.
Light.
Yes, it's a light.
We had no equipment whatsoever.
Nothing.
Nothing.
Absolutely nothing.
We had two or three cans of dried paint and probably a half a dozen flats that were old and beat up.
We had absolutely nothing.
Nothing.
No money, no budget, no nothing.
I'm not complaining.
You asked me a question, and I'm telling you the truth, you see.
That's what I'm asking for.
Yeah.
Okay, now, to get the perspective, you used the assembly hall, which was located approximately where All Faith Chapel is.
That's right.
How long did you continue to use that building?
I can't remember, so help me, Hannah.
I can't remember.
Okay.
For quite a while.
Let's leave it that way.
Well, let's say this way.
If you can find out when they tore the thing down or when it fell down, that's when we moved out and we had to.
Okay.
When they tore that building down, where did you go?
Guyon.
Guyon.
We didn't go to Guyon, no, permanently, though we fiddled around.
We were in the basement of the MSC, and we were, you know,
We were without a home, to tell you the truth.
You see, at that time, they were still giving movies in Guyon Hall, beginning in the afternoon and running all afternoon and up into the night.
This was a daily occurrence?
Oh, yes.
Yes, every day.
Every day.
So we didn't have, we had the basement.
Eventually we had the basement.
Then when they stopped giving movies over there, which date I don't remember, I was asked to take over the supervision, let's say, of Guyon Hall.
So I did.
And that became the home of the Aggie Players.
And then we...
created a fallout theater.
And that was a theater whereby any student on this campus could write a play or could do a play in the basement for the public.
And we'd give him any equipment that he needed.
I mean, this was open anyway.
We called it the fallout theater.
And you see those little black books here?
Those are all scripts of fallout theater productions done absolutely by students.
No, they weren't all written by students.
Some of them were.
But they were directed, and the light plots, the acting, and everything else was done by students.
With a little help from us, if they wanted a little help, we'd go in and help them out a little.
And that's what the fallout theater was.
Is that still in the business?
Yes, but we don't really have a fallout shelter for them to operate in.
We've done a few plays over at Forum there that we claim are fallout theater, but I don't like to...
I didn't want to lose the name of the fallout theater.
You see, we have the Aggie plays, we have the fallout theater, we have Children's Creative Dramatics, we have Children's Theater, and we have...
the premium players.
We have those five groups working within the structure of the theater arts section of the Department of English.
And they've all been quite successful over the last few years.
See, we run this Children's Creative Dramatics and the premium players in the summer.
The Children's Creative Dramatics is run for the community of College Station.
That's right, yes.
I'm somewhat familiar with that because both of my sons participated briefly.
Yes.
But that is done by students primarily?
No, no, no.
I hire people to do that that have been trained by me or us in the area of Children's Trade in the Mass.
I teach Children's Trade in the Mass.
You teach it on campus?
Yes.
And then students who have been in that
Well, they've got to have more than that before I'll hire them.
Well, I mean, they have been in that.
Oh, yes, yes.
And then you hired them for the summer to...
The lady that's been working downtown is...
Been working down there, I don't know, five or six years, the same lady down there.
And that's where the creating dramatics is for a specific age group, which goes up to what?
Five to ten.
Five to ten.
Well, five to eleven, but we don't get many of those eleven, twelve-year-olds.
And then the premier players are for older.
Teeners from thirteen on, in high school, the high school kiddos, you see.
And we do two plays a summer with them.
Two full-length plays.
And it's really a...
I don't like the word workshop, but it's really a workshop in theater for teenagers here in the community.
And who...
is in charge of the premier players.
Well, I've had my assistant in charge of the premier players the last several years, ever since I hired him, Bob Wink.
And I believe one of your premier players productions is usually a melodrama.
Yeah.
Well, the last three or four years, yeah, we use a melodrama.
Because they're fun, and it's a summertime type of production.
Yeah.
Yeah.
What was the financial footing, financial basis, let's say, for the Aggie players when you took over?
I just got through telling you.
Well, we didn't get anything.
Nothing.
I believe you said before we turned on the tape they were in a $600 in debt.
That's right.
And they were in a student activity then, and I just went to the head fellow there who was Spike White, a nice guy, and I said, Spike, I'm not going to dig around for this $600.
He said, all right, we'll just wipe it off.
Tabula rasa.
So he wiped it off and I started with nothing.
So you had no money.
No money.
No equipment other than six flights.
Yeah.
And so you had to then, I suppose, do a good bit of scrounging at first.
That is a beautiful word, and we've been doing it for 25 years.
Did you get any amount of money from the student services?
Yes.
Eventually, we got some money from the exchange store profit.
They looked very favorably upon us, and they gave us, for quite a while, they gave us quite a bit of money.
And then when we became a little bit more affluent, or not affluent, but a little more self-supporting, they sort of came down, down, down, down, which they should have.
They were perfectly right in cutting their allowance to us.
But that's the only one.
Just recently, in the last three years, three or four years maybe, we have a small budget in the Department of English.
And incidentally, there was a gentleman out in West Texas who has, for the last five years, been sending me, as a personal thing, I think, because his daughter was my secretary once,
And he's a fairly affluent old gentleman.
He even sent me $500 every year.
And I've been using that for the premium players and the children's career dramatics.
And I've been getting some money from the last several years.
When I say I, I mean we.
We've been getting some money in the last several years from the College Station Recreation Council.
That would be for the premier players.
And the children.
Yes, right.
